# **ANTHEM— THM CTF — WRITEUP**

![][image1]

Hello everyone\! This is a beginner-friendly room from the TryHackMe platform titled “**Anthem**.”

This room is classified as easy and is a walkthrough-type challenge. It took me a bit to complete and was a fun room, and I hope this write-up helps guide you through the process\!

My goal is to help you understand each step and provide clear explanations so that anyone, whether a beginner or experienced, can follow along and understand the reasoning behind each action. I hope this write-up makes the process smoother and easier to grasp.

Enough talk — let’s dive right in, and I hope you enjoy the journey\! :)

First, we deploy the machine. While it’s booting up, go ahead and open your terminal tab and get it ready.

Once it’s up, let’s copy the IP address and connect to the network. We encounter a web page with some image and text.

I initiate an Nmap scan and run a Feroxbuster scan.

![][image2]

***nmap \-A \-p- 10.10.55.249***

* Open ports found:  
* **80 (HTTP)**  
* **3389 (RDP)**

**![][image3]**

On looking through the webpage, it contains subpages like **blogs,categories and tags** related to articles.

***gobuster dir \-u http://10.10.55.249/ \-w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt***

In the **blog section**, one of the blog posts, we even see an **email address\!**

**![][image4]**

Now in the webpage I decide to run robots.txt, as the webpage contains the word **“Crawlers”**, which hints at **robots.txt**

**![][image5]**

***http://10.10.55.249/robots.txt***

It **reveals** the **CMS in use** → **Umbraco**.

The **homepage text** mentions **anthem.com**.

* **Domain name \= anthem.com**

Next, on inspecting the source code :

![][image6]

![][image7]

Searching for **Admin Panel**, we find a **poem** with the word **“admin”** in it.

![][image8]

* **Hint:** Poem might be a **clue**\!

So I Copy & paste the poem into a search engine → It refers to Solomon Grundy.

![][image9]

This gives the username clue, we even remember seeing the email in the blog page :

*jd@anthem.com*

**Following the same pattern**:

* **Solomon Grundy → SG**  
* **Admin Email → sg@anthem.com**

And, this works \!

![][image10]

Now referring to the gobuster scan and we see some locations:

![][image11]

**Flag 1:** Under /authors

![][image12]

**Flag 2:** Inspect the **homepage**

**![][image13]**

**Flags 3 & 4:** Found in **two blog pages**

**![][image14]**

**![][image15]**

Now we see the flags in these aspects.

![][image16]

Next utilizing the CMS system:

Go to:

![][image17]

***http://10.10.55.249/umbraco/\#/login***

Use credentials found earlier:

![][image18]

* **Username:** sg@anthem.com  
* **Password:** UmbracoIsTheBest\!

Nothing useful inside Umbraco CMS

* Remember: Nmap showed no domain is configured.  
* Try RDP (Port 3389).

## **Remote Desktop (RDP) Access**

**![][image19]**

Connect using **rdesktop**

**![][image20]**

I had an issue with the screenshots but below are the steps what I performed :

* Open **File Explorer**.  
* Go to **This PC** → **Local Disk C**.  
* Click **View** → Enable **Hidden Files**.  
* Open **Backup** Folder.  
* Click **Restore**.  
* A popup appears.  
* **Right-click → Properties → Security → Edit**.  
* **Add User:** SG  
* **We get the admin password\!**  
* **Log back into the system using new admin credentials**:  
* **Username:** Administrator  
* **Password:** ChangeMeBaby1MoreTime  
* **Access the Root File & Capture the Final Flag**
